Sorry but the answer could be negative, as I know MSBuild itself doesn&#39;t have the ability to read data like Version-number from `AndroidManifest.xml`. In other words, it&#39;s not supported by msbuild. 

MSBuild can access any [property](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/msbuild/msbuild-properties?view=vs-2019) defined in project file or imported targets file, but it can&#39;t access `AndroidManifest.xml` file. And there&#39;s no official [msbuild task](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/msbuild/msbuild-tasks?view=vs-2019) can to this for us, so if you do need this behavior, we have to code ourselves to read the version info from that xml file. Topics about this: [one](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/642293/how-do-i-read-and-parse-an-xml-file-in-c), [two](https://support.microsoft.com/en-sg/help/307548/how-to-read-xml-from-a-file-by-using-visual-c), [three](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47742118/read-an-xml-file-line-by-line-and-add-to-a-list)...(Too many topics online talk about this, so I don&#39;t talk too much here, if you meet some issue about coding that, let me know:-
))

 Here&#39;re two possible ways after that coding:

1.Create a `.exe` file with code to execute the renaming job, and call the .exe in a post-build event

2.Write a [custom task](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/msbuild/task-writing?view=vs-2019) named CustomTask, and add this script into the project file to call this task after `build` or `SignAndroidPackage` target.

      &lt;UsingTask TaskName=&quot;CustomTask.CustomTask&quot;
            AssemblyFile=&quot;path\CustomTask.dll&quot;/&gt;
      
      &lt;!--Maybe it should be AfterTargets=&quot;SignAndroidPackage&quot;--&gt;
      &lt;Target Name=&quot;CustomTarget&quot; AfterTargets=&quot;Build&quot;&gt;
        &lt;CustomTask/&gt;
      &lt;/Target&gt;

May it makes some help.

Because when the final `}` of a function declaration is reached, the interpreter sees the whole function declaration that comes before it as a *single statement*. If you put anything after the `}`, it will be interpreted as a separate, standalone, unused expression:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function foo() {
    }(&#39;bar&#39;)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

This creates a `bar` string, but the interpreter doesn&#39;t do anything with it - it&#39;s like

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function foo() {
    }
    &#39;bar&#39;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The string is declared, but not used anywhere.

