&gt; &quot;I understand how to open a file, ...&quot;

No, not really, one fundamental rule of coding is you *&quot;Do not hardcode filenames or use magic-numbers&quot;*. That means you do not want to:

    secretMessage = fopen(&quot;C://Users/anyah/Fall2019/ECE_114/GreatGatsby.txt&quot;, &quot;r&quot;);

Passing arguments to your program is why you have arguments to `main()`, e.g.

    int main (int argc, char **argv)

Simply provide the filename to read from as an argument to your program (or read from `stdin` by default). To do that you can do something similar to:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    ...
    int main (int argc, char **argv) {
        ...
        /* use filename provided as 1st argument (stdin by default) */
        FILE *fp = argc &gt; 1 ? fopen (argv[1], &quot;r&quot;) : stdin;
        
        if (!fp) {  /* validate file open for reading */
            perror (&quot;file open failed&quot;);
            return 1;
        }

At this point you have finished opening your file (or are reading from `stdin`) and you have ***validated*** that the file stream is open for reading.

To store multiple words without allocating storage dynamically, you will need to use a 2D array where each row holds a word, and the columns are adequate to hold any word plus the *nul-terminating* character so the array of characters in that row can be treated as a string. The longest *non-medical* word in the Unabridged Dictionary is 29-characters (so a total number of columns of 30 will do, but the next power-of-two of `32` is fine)

Since you do not use *magic-numbers* in your code, `#define` one (or more) constants as needed. You can use a global `enum` to accomplish the same thing. To provide storage for 128 words of 31-characters or less you could do:

    /* if you need a constant, #define one (or more) */
    #define ROWS 128    /* max no. of words to read  */
    #define COLS 32     /* max no. of chars per-word */
    ...
        char words[ROWS][COLS] = {&quot;&quot;};  /* 2D array to hold words */

With your file open and storage declared to hold your words, you now simply read each character with `fgetc` (or read a line at a time with `fgets`) and collect characters until a `&#39;_&#39;`, a `&#39;\n&#39;` or `EOF` is found. To protect your `words` array bounds you make sure you attempt to fill no more than `ROWS` words. For each word, you protect the column bounds by ensuring you read no more than `COL-1` characters (the `-1` to save space for the *nul-terminating* character)

Putting that together and using a couple of counter variables, you could do:

        while (row &lt; ROWS) {                /* while rows left in array */
            int c, col = 0;                 /* character c, column counter */
            /* loop over each char in word */
            for (c = fgetc(fp); col &lt; COLS - 1; col++, c = fgetc(fp)) {
                if (c == EOF)               /* if EOF jump out of nested loops */
                    goto done;
                if (c == &#39;_&#39; || c == &#39;\n&#39;)  /* if char is &#39;_&#39; or &#39;\n&#39;, get next */
                    break;
                words[row][col] = c;        /* assign char to current word */
            }
            words[row++][col] = 0;          /* nul-terminate, advance word count */
        }
        done:;      /* goto label to jump to */

(**note:** the only direct way to jump out of nested loops is to use the old `goto` statement. The only limitation is that you do not attempt to jump out of a function, breaking nested loops is fine)

A complete example could be:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    
    /* if you need a constant, #define one (or more) */
    #define ROWS 128    /* max no. of words to read  */
    #define COLS 32     /* max no. of chars per-word */
    
    int main (int argc, char **argv) {
        
        char words[ROWS][COLS] = {&quot;&quot;};  /* 2D array to hold words */
        int row = 0, i;                 /* row (word) and loop counter */
        /* use filename provided as 1st argument (stdin by default) */
        FILE *fp = argc &gt; 1 ? fopen (argv[1], &quot;r&quot;) : stdin;
        
        if (!fp) {  /* validate file open for reading */
            perror (&quot;file open failed&quot;);
            return 1;
        }
        
        while (row &lt; ROWS) {                /* while rows left in array */
            int c, col = 0;                 /* character c, column counter */
            /* loop over each char in word */
            for (c = fgetc(fp); col &lt; COLS - 1; col++, c = fgetc(fp)) {
                if (c == EOF)               /* if EOF jump out of nested loops */
                    goto done;
                if (c == &#39;_&#39; || c == &#39;\n&#39;)  /* if char is &#39;_&#39; or &#39;\n&#39;, get next */
                    break;
                words[row][col] = c;        /* assign char to current word */
            }
            words[row++][col] = 0;          /* nul-terminate, advance word count */
        }
        done:;      /* goto label to jump to */
        
        if (fp != stdin)   /* close file if not stdin */
            fclose (fp);
        
        for (i = row-1; i &gt;= 0; i--)
            printf ((i != row - 1) &gt; 0 ? &quot; %s&quot; : &quot;%s&quot;, words[i]);
        putchar (&#39;\n&#39;);
    }

The final loop just outputs the words in reverse order and the *ternary* in the `printf` statement just ensures you don&#39;t print a space before the first word output.

**Example Input File**

    $ cat dat/backwardsfleas.txt
    cat_lucky_none_has_cat_my_fleas_has_dog_my

**Example Use/Output**

    $ ./bin/arrayrevwords dat/backwardsfleas.txt
    my dog has fleas my cat has none lucky cat

